{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17652281","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17652281"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T21:34:41+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T21:34:41+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18530"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18530","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18530"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11262"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75540"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11262","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11262"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18530"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61055"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4940"},{"type":"tags","id":"4945"},{"type":"tags","id":"7671"},{"type":"tags","id":"10697"},{"type":"tags","id":"10715"},{"type":"tags","id":"10716"},{"type":"tags","id":"10960"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"26113"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26117"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75540","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/75540"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EDifferent types of mutagens can damage DNA through distinct molecular mechanisms. Understanding these mechanisms is crucial for comprehending both natural mutation processes and environmental hazards.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary mechanism by which ultraviolet radiation causes DNA mutations?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Formation of thymine dimers","Deamination of cytosine","Base pair intercalation","Oxidation of guanine bases","Creation of DNA strand breaks"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe primary mechanism by which ultraviolet (UV) radiation causes DNA mutations is through \u003Cstrong\u003Eformation of thymine dimers\u003C/strong\u003E. When adjacent thymine bases absorb UV energy, they can form covalent bonds between each other, distorting the DNA double helix. If not repaired, this often leads to characteristic C\u2192T mutations during DNA replication.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect mechanisms can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECreation of DNA strand breaks\u003C/strong\u003E - This is primarily associated with ionising radiation, not UV radiation\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBase pair intercalation\u003C/strong\u003E - This is characteristic of certain chemical mutagens that insert between DNA bases\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDeamination of cytosine\u003C/strong\u003E - While this can occur spontaneously or through chemical means, it is not a primary mechanism of UV damage\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOxidation of guanine bases\u003C/strong\u003E - This typically occurs through reactive oxygen species, not direct UV exposure\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile UV radiation can cause other types of DNA damage, thymine dimer formation is its most common and characteristic mutagenic effect. These dimers are normally repaired by nucleotide excision repair mechanisms, but when repair fails, mutations can result.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Ultraviolet radiation primarily causes thymine dimers in DNA, leading to characteristic C\u2192T mutations.","Ionising radiation primarily causes double-strand DNA breaks through direct damage and free radical formation.","Chemical mutagens like ethidium bromide typically act by intercalating between DNA base pairs."],"references":["Turnpenny PD, Ellard S. Emery\u0027s Elements of Medical Genetics E-Book: Elsevier Health Sciences; 2011","Laughery MF, Wilson HE, Sewell A, Stevison S, Wyrick JJ. The Surprising Diversity of UV-Induced Mutations. Advanced Genetics. 2024;5(2):2300205. Available at: https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/full/10.1002/ggn2.202300205"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61055"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18530"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61055","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/61055"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-30T09:47:35+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-30T09:50:42+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11262"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75540"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"